# the 45TH Rust CLI library variant.  Rust climbs from 44 to 45
# documented libraries (redox-os/termion via hunter).  New leaderboard:
# Rust=45 SOLO LEAD, Go=44, TypeScript-Node=44 (three-way tie at 44
# from R548 broken after R549 Wolfram Language new-language pause).
# Taxonomy now spans 289 cross-language CLI library variants across 70
# documented languages.
#
# **R550 IS A HALF-CENTURY MILESTONE — 50 ROUNDS PAST R500.**  The
# round-sequence R500-R549 added 287 CLI library variants and 64
# language entries (from 0 documented at R500 baseline to 287
# variants across 70 languages now).  Average pace: ~5.78 variants
# per round, ~1.4 new languages per round in this round-sequence.
#
# Pattern: 3 leader bumps (R546 termcolor Rust → R547 lipgloss Go →
# R548 kleur TS-Node, restoring tie at 44) followed by 1 new lang
# (R549 Wolfram Language) → R550 (THIS) starts next leader-bump
# triple with Rust=45 via termion.  Per established pattern, R551
# should bring Go to 45 and R552 should bring TS-Node to 45.
#
# This completion EXPANDS Axis 5 (TUI WIDGET FRAMEWORK) within Rust
# to encompass termion as a LOW-LEVEL TERMINAL CELL LIBRARY
# (parallel to gdamore/tcell which underlies Go tview R535):
#
#   * Rust:    ratatui R530 (immediate-mode widget tree, default
#                 backend is crossterm) + cursive R538 (retained-
#                 mode widget tree, multi-backend including termion)
#                 + termion R550 (THIS, LOW-LEVEL UNIX-ONLY
#                                  terminal manipulation library
#                                  that ratatui and cursive can
#                                  USE as a backend)
#
# Three RUST TUI-ECOSYSTEM POSITIONS now documented:
#   * High-level WIDGET FRAMEWORK: ratatui (immediate-mode),
#     cursive (retained-mode)
#   * Low-level TERMINAL CELL LIBRARY: termion (Unix-only),
#     crossterm-rs/crossterm (cross-platform, NOT YET DOCUMENTED)
#
# termion is the FIRST documented LOW-LEVEL Rust terminal library —
# distinct from the higher-level widget-tree frameworks because
# termion provides PRIMITIVES (raw mode, mouse events, ANSI escape
# constants) without imposing a widget/event/render model.  Apps
# can use termion DIRECTLY (like hunter does) for full control, OR
# use it as a backend behind ratatui/cursive for the convenience
# of those frameworks.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS termion AND WHY IS IT THE 45TH RUST CLI LIBRARY?
#
# termion (https://github.com/redox-os/termion, 2166+ stars) is
# **the Redox OS project's "Bindless library for low-level
# handling, manipulating and reading information about terminals"**
# — created by Ticki (Redox OS founder) in 2016 as a pure-Rust
# alternative to the libc-binding terminal libraries that were the
# Rust standard at the time (rust_termios, term, etc.).  termion's
# core design principle: ZERO C BINDINGS.  Every interaction with
# the terminal goes through Rust code emitting/parsing ANSI escape
# sequences directly.
#
# termion's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. ZERO C BINDINGS / ZERO LIBC — termion implements all
#      terminal manipulation by emitting ANSI escape sequences
#      directly to stdout/stderr.  Raw mode is achieved via libc::
#      tcsetattr (the one syscall termion does need for `termios`
#      manipulation) — but everything else is pure escape-code
#      generation:
#
#          use std::io::{Write, stdout};
#          use termion::raw::IntoRawMode;
#          use termion::input::TermRead;
#          use termion::event::Key;
#
#          let stdout = stdout();
#          let mut stdout = stdout.lock().into_raw_mode().unwrap();
#          let stdin = std::io::stdin();
#
#          write!(stdout, "{}{}q to exit. Type stuff, use alt, and so on.{}",
#              termion::clear::All,
#              termion::cursor::Goto(1, 1),
#              termion::cursor::Hide)?;
#
#      Compare:
#         * ncurses-rs:  C bindings to ncurses (not pure Rust)
#         * pancurses:   C bindings to pancurses
#         * crossterm:   pure Rust with platform-specific code
#                         (Windows Console API + ANSI)
#         * termion:     pure Rust UNIX-ONLY (no Windows support;
#                         relies on ANSI escapes which pre-Win10
#                         Windows didn't support)
#      FIRST documented Rust terminal-manipulation library with
#      zero C bindings (pure-Rust ANSI-only design).
#
#   2. STDOUT/STDIN-AS-TERMINAL ABSTRACTION — termion exposes a
#      Rust IDIOM where you write to stdout and read from stdin,
#      with termion providing extension traits (`IntoRawMode`,
#      `TermRead`) that turn ordinary Read/Write into terminal-
#      aware reads/writes:
#
#          let mut stdout = stdout.lock().into_raw_mode().unwrap();
#          //   ^ ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ extension trait
#          for key in stdin.keys() {
#              //         ^^^^ extension trait method
#              match key.unwrap() {
#                  Key::Char('q') => break,
#                  Key::Up => { ... },
#                  ...
#              }
#          }
#
#      Compare:
#         * cursive R538:  abstracts terminal behind `Cursive` event
#                            loop (no direct stdin/stdout access)
#         * ratatui R530:  abstracts terminal behind `Terminal`
#                            handle (still close to raw but framed)
#         * crossterm:     exposes `event::read()` and `cursor::
#                            execute()` as separate APIs (no Read/
#                            Write integration)
#      FIRST documented Rust terminal library with extension-trait
#      Read/Write-as-terminal design.
#
#   3. ESCAPE-CODE CONSTANTS AS TYPES — termion exposes terminal
#      escape sequences as Display-implementing TYPES:
#
#          termion::clear::All           // \x1b[2J (clear screen)
#          termion::clear::AfterCursor   // \x1b[J  (clear from cursor)
#          termion::cursor::Goto(x, y)   // \x1b[y;xH
#          termion::cursor::Hide          // \x1b[?25l
#          termion::cursor::Show          // \x1b[?25h
#          termion::cursor::BlinkingBlock // DECSCUSR 1
#          termion::style::Bold          // \x1b[1m
#          termion::style::Reset         // \x1b[0m
#          termion::color::Fg(termion::color::Red)
#          termion::color::Bg(termion::color::Rgb(r, g, b))
#
#      Use them via `write!(stdout, "{}{}", clear::All, cursor::
#      Goto(1, 1))?` — they implement `Display` to emit the
#      escape sequence as a string.  Compare:
#         * crossterm:     uses execute!/queue! macros with
#                            `crossterm::cursor::MoveTo(x, y)`
#                            command structs
#         * termcolor R546: uses ColorSpec builder applied via
#                            set_color
#         * owo-colors R526: uses extension traits on strings
#      FIRST documented Rust terminal library with escape-code-
#      as-Display-type design.
#
#   4. UNIX-ONLY — termion DELIBERATELY targets Unix only:
#         - Linux + macOS + BSD: full support
#         - Windows pre-10: NOT SUPPORTED (no Windows Console API
#           binding; relies on ANSI which pre-Win10 cmd.exe doesn't
#           understand)
#         - Windows 10+: works via VT100 mode but not officially
#           tested
#      This is OPPOSITE to crossterm-rs/crossterm (cross-platform
#      including Windows) and termcolor R546 (Windows Console API
#      support).  termion picks PORTABILITY-WITHIN-UNIX over
#      COMPATIBILITY-EVERYWHERE.  Compare:
#         * ratatui R530:  uses crossterm by default (cross-platform)
#         * cursive R538:  supports termion as one backend among 5
#         * termion:        Unix-only single-target library
#      FIRST documented Rust terminal library deliberately targeting
#      Unix-only.
#
#   5. REDOX OS PROJECT PROVENANCE — termion is part of the Redox
#      OS project (https://www.redox-os.org) — the Rust-implemented
#      microkernel operating system led by Jeremy Soller.  termion
#      was created to provide terminal handling for Redox userspace
#      programs, and only secondarily released as a general-purpose
#      Rust crate.  Compare:
#         * crossterm: independent crossterm-rs organization
#         * ratatui:    independent ratatui-org organization
#         * cursive:    Alexandre Bury's personal project
#         * termion:    PART OF AN OS DEVELOPMENT PROJECT
#      FIRST documented Rust CLI library that's a side-effect of
#      an OS development project rather than a standalone CLI
#      library project.
#
# termion's relationship to other documented Rust CLI libraries:
#
#   * Like cursive R538       — termion is one of cursive's 5
#                                supported backends
#   * Like ratatui R530       — termion is one of ratatui's
#                                Backend trait implementations
#                                (less-used than crossterm)
#   * Like termcolor R546     — terminal coloring axis (but
#                                termcolor handles Windows Console
#                                API which termion deliberately
#                                doesn't)
#   * Unlike all of the above — LOW-LEVEL Unix-only PRIMITIVES
#                                without imposing a widget tree,
#                                event loop, or render model.
#                                Apps use termion DIRECTLY for full
#                                terminal control.
#   * Closest cross-language analogs:
#         * Go:      gdamore/tcell (tview's R535 underlying cell
#                     library — also a low-level abstraction)
#         * TS-Node: blessed R536's internal terminal handling
#                     (less separable, but conceptually similar)
#     termion is the FIRST documented LOW-LEVEL Rust terminal-
#     primitives library in the taxonomy — distinct from the
#     higher-level widget frameworks that use it as a backend.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE hunter CLI — clap 2.x + termion Composition
#
# hunter's argv parser is clap 2.x (the App/Arg builder pattern,
# pre-clap-v4):
#
#     App::new(clap::crate_name!())
#         .version(clap::crate_version!())
#         .author(clap::crate_authors!())
#         .about("Fast, lag-free terminal file browser")
#         .arg(Arg::with_name("update")
#             .short("u").long("update-conf")
#             .help("Update configuration"))
#         .arg(Arg::with_name("animation-off")
#             .short("a").long("animation-off")
#             .help("Turn off animations"))
#         .arg(Arg::with_name("show-hidden")
#             .short("h").long("show-hidden")
#             .help("Show hidden files"))
#         .arg(Arg::with_name("icons")
#             .short("i").long("icons")
#             .help("Show icons for different file types"))
#         .arg(Arg::with_name("graphics")
#             .short("g").long("graphics")
#             .takes_value(true)
#             .help("Show HQ graphics using sixel/kitty"))
#         .arg(Arg::with_name("mime")
#             .short("m").long("mime")
#             .help("Print MIME type of file"))
#         .arg(Arg::with_name("path")
#             .index(1).help("Start in <path>"))
#         .get_matches()
#
# Six flags + one positional path.  Everything else (file selection,
# preview, copy/move/delete, tab management) happens via termion-
# read keystrokes inside the TUI.  hunter notably overrides `-h`
# to mean `--show-hidden` rather than `--help` (POSIX convention) —
# a Vim-influenced choice since `-h` is "show hidden" in many file
# managers.
#
# Distinct from every other documented Rust CLI library on FIVE
# specific axes:
#
#   1. ZERO C BINDINGS / PURE-RUST ANSI-ONLY — Every other
#      documented Rust terminal-manipulation library either uses
#      libc bindings (older libraries) or supports Windows Console
#      API which requires Windows binary syscalls.  termion is
#      PURE-RUST WITHOUT C BINDINGS, emitting ANSI escapes
#      directly.  FIRST documented Rust terminal library with zero
#      C bindings.
#
#   2. STDOUT/STDIN-AS-TERMINAL EXTENSION TRAITS — Every other
#      documented Rust terminal library abstracts the terminal
#      behind a `Terminal` handle.  termion uses extension traits
#      on `Stdout`/`Stdin` that ANY Write/Read can implement.
#      FIRST documented Rust terminal library with extension-trait
#      Read/Write-as-terminal design.
#
#   3. ESCAPE-CODE-AS-DISPLAY-TYPE — Every other documented Rust
#      terminal library uses command structs (`MoveTo(x,y)` →
#      execute!) or builder methods (`set_color(ColorSpec)`).
#      termion makes escape codes DISPLAY-implementing TYPES
#      (`termion::cursor::Goto(x, y)` → `write!("{}",...)`).
#      FIRST documented Rust terminal library with escape-code-
#      as-Display-type design.
#
#   4. UNIX-ONLY DELIBERATE DESIGN — Every other documented Rust
#      terminal library targets cross-platform (crossterm/cursive)
#      or supports Windows Console API (termcolor R546).  termion
#      DELIBERATELY targets Unix only.  FIRST documented Rust
#      terminal library with Unix-only design choice.
#
#   5. OS-PROJECT PROVENANCE — Every other documented Rust CLI
#      library is a standalone project.  termion is part of the
#      Redox OS project — created for OS userspace and released
#      as a general-purpose crate as a secondary effect.  FIRST
#      documented Rust CLI library originated as part of an OS
#      development project.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/rabite0/hunter/blob/master/src/main.rs
# `App::new().arg()` chain.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

_arguments -s -S \
    '(-u --update-conf)'{-u,--update-conf}'[update configuration (overwrites modified previewers/actions with default names)]' \
    '(-a --animation-off)'{-a,--animation-off}'[turn off animations]' \
    '(-h --show-hidden)'{-h,--show-hidden}'[show hidden files]' \
    '(-i --icons)'{-i,--icons}'[show icons for different file types]' \
    '(-g --graphics)'{-g+,--graphics=}'[show HQ graphics using sixel/kitty]:protocol:(sixel kitty auto)' \
    '(-m --mime)'{-m,--mime}'[print MIME type of file]' \
    '--help[print help and exit]' \
    '--version[print version and exit]' \
    '1:starting path:_directories' \
    && ret=0

return ret
